comment: I think the worst thing about this case is that they never found her body. I also think the comments trying to pin the blame on anybody other than Quiles and his wife are unhelpful. Let‚Äôs be realistic for once. Parents have jobs. My parents worked. My mother had three jobs and my father worked from 5 am to 5 pm everyday. My sister and I spent time at various friends and families houses. Why? Because it takes a village. And i‚Äôm grateful to have never had to experience any form of abuse or predators around me. I could trust all the men and women in my family. That‚Äôs how it should be. But unfortunately it‚Äôs not and a lot of parents are trying their best. Blaming her mother asking her why she wasn‚Äôt there to protect her‚Ä¶if her mother is a single mother I am not shocked she didn‚Äôt have time to track her daughters every move. Shoot as a teenager, my parents never knew where I was honestly. I was home most of the time but sometimes I‚Äôd sneak out or do other things. It‚Äôs life. Kids and teens should be able to experience life and parents should be able to give them that experience without fear of abuse or even death. We are making our society worse everyday. So when we sit here and point fingers, I laugh. Because people used to be able to just leave their kids at a neighbors house. People used to be able to actually trust their own family. We‚Äôve destroyed our society as we know it and then want to point blame on anybody but ourselves. It could very easily be you or your own kid. And I pray nobody has to experience the loss of a life. Especially in this way. No amount of ‚Äúwhere was her parents‚Äù will bring her back.

comment:
*****YOU ALL MISSED IT!*****

Remember when they first went to his house that nigh, when he and his wife were so helpful and all, inviting the investigators in, offering them food and something to drink? He spoke highly of Iyana, saying she was smart and all, even passionately mentioning her as "his" niece and that was before he made the "38 pair" comment, that sent up red flags for the investigators.

But, when the detectives started to make him aware of DNA evidence, putting the heat on him, he looked down, shook his head, reposition himself in his chair, all tell-tell signs of a guilty individual. 

THEN he said something at the (13:24) point of the video, that "I" caught immediately!

He literally stated, "I have nothing to do with 'THAT' girl disappearing, whatsoever, whatsoever."

"THAT GIRL"?

She was no longer "HIS" niece, but "THAT GIRL!"

Murderers/serial killers must see their victims as an object and NOT a human being for them to murder them. So, in his twisted mind, she was no longer his niece, not even human, but an "object," getting in the way of his family's life!

That's when I knew he did it!

Mothers, fathers, please watch your children! Pay attention to who they interact with daily.

comment:
I do have a problem with a death penalty sentence without a body. ‚ÄúNo body no crime‚Äù is obviously BS and does not equal reasonable doubt in and of itself, but if that one in a billion miracle happens and she‚Äôs alive‚Ä¶ he can‚Äôt be un-executed.

Disclosure: that‚Äôs my issue with the death penalty in general, it can‚Äôt be remedied if the verdict is later proven wrong. Essentially, if the state executes an innocent person, they have made the people accessory to homicide and I don‚Äôt think that is outweighed by any/all of the (generally valid) arguments for a death sentence.

To be clear, I do not disagree with the moral argument that sometimes a person does something so horrific that they deserve death if convicted; this case definitely being such a situation. I do, however, believe that absent a way to prove guilt beyond ANY doubt no criminal justice system should be allowed to make a mistake that cannot be remedied. A LOT of executed criminals have been exonerated by DNA evidence that was unavailable at the time of the conviction.

comment:
This. So one time my son had wandered off when he was being watched by his own dad...I had run to the store. When we realize he had just walked away (we were at a playground), I literally lost it. I called 911 right away. I was hysterical...his dad was just acting aloof. Obviously I'm not completely blaming him since the kids were playing, and we think he walked over to my car when I got back. But when you think you're missing a child or something like that bad is happening, the way people react says it all. I was hysterical and it was only a few minutes!! His dad was another story, he was acting aloof bc it might be HIS fault.
And I always think of that when you see the Chris Watts type cases on YouTube where the people are acting like they don't know where their own kid is but also they're not bothered üôÑ HELLO?! Once that happens to you you're going to freak tf out.
